Java Fundamentals Quiz: Introduction to Java

1. What type of programming language is Java?
a) Low-level
b) Assembly-based
c) High-level
d) Machine-specific

Answer: c) High-level
Java is a high-level language because it abstracts complex machine instructions into human-readable code.

2. Which programming paradigm does Java follow?
a) Procedural
b) Functional
c) Object-oriented
d) Structural

Answer: c) Object-oriented
 Java is built around the concept of objects and classes, following the object-oriented programming paradigm.

3. What does WORA stand for in Java?
a) Write once, read anywhere
b) Write once, run anywhere
c) Write on random access
d) Write once, reuse always

Answer: b) Write once, run anywhere
WORA means Java programs can run on any device that has a Java Virtual Machine (JVM).

4. Which of the following is NOT a key feature of Java?
a) Platform dependent
b) Secure
c) Robust
d) Multi-threaded

Answer: a) Platform dependent
Java is platform-independent, so “platform dependent” is not one of its features.

5.In the example program, what is the name of the class?
Public class Main {
		Public static void main(String[] args) {
		System.out.println(“HelloWorld”);
}
}

a) Hello
b) HelloWorld
c) main
d) System

Answer: b) HelloWorld
The class name in the code is HelloWorld, which must match the filename.






6. What does the following line do in the Java program?

System.out.println("Hello, World!");


a) Reads input from the user
b) Prints text to the console
c) Creates a new class
d) Declares a variable

Answer: b) Prints text to the console
System.out.println() displays the specified text on the screen.

7. What keyword is used to define a class in Java?
a) def
b) function
c) class
d) public

Answer: c) class
The class keyword is used to declare or define a new class in Java.

8. What is the main purpose of the main() method in Java?
a) To store data
b) To start the execution of the program
c) To handle exceptions
d) To define variables

Answer: b) To start the execution of the program
The main() method acts as the entry point where the program begins execution.

9. Which of these features makes Java suitable for concurrent programming?
a) Platform Independence
b) Multi-threading
c) Robustness
d) Security

Answer: b) Multi-threading
Multi-threading allows Java to perform multiple tasks simultaneously in a single program.

10. Which statement best describes Java’s robustness?
a) It runs only on specific operating systems.
b) It has weak memory management.
c) It can handle errors and manage memory efficiently.
d) It does not support error handling.

Answer: c) It can handle errors and manage memory efficiently.
Java is robust because it prevents crashes through strong memory management and exception handling.
